Photo by Ami Vitale @amivitale | A giraffe frolics outside Doulouwal Peulh, Niger, a village about 50 miles from the capital of Niamey, where the endangered West African giraffe lives. It is part of the Niger's "giraffe zone," a government-defined region where giraffes and humans coexist. There are currently only 600 West African giraffe alive on the planet. Creating a satellite population in Niger's Gadabedji Biosphere Reserve was vital to helping the long-term survival prospects of the subspecies. 
Learn more, including how to help, by following @amivitale @giraffe_conservation and @sdzsafaripark.
@thephotosociety @natgeoimagecollection #protectgiraffes #DontLetThemDisappear #giraffe #savegiraffes #niger

Photo by Simon Norfolk @simonnorfolkstudio I The plague outbreak in the Derbyshire village of Eyam, northern England, began in 1665 when a flea-infested bundle of cloth arrived from London for the local tailor. Within a week his assistant, George Viccars, was dead, and more began dying in the household soon after. As the disease spread, the villagers turned for leadership to their rector, the Rev. William Mompesson, and Puritan minister Thomas Stanley. In an act of tremendous bravery, they decided to quarantine the entire village to prevent further spread of the disease to neighboring communities. The plague in Eyam raged for 14 months and claimed the lives of at least 260, over one-third of the population.

Seen here: The Riley graves, a walled enclosure on the outskirts of Eyam, holds the bodies of Elizabeth Hancock's husband and six children, all of whom died within eight days of each other. Because of the high risk of infecting her neighbors, she had the traumatic task of dragging the bodies from her farmhouse and burying them herself. Follow me @simonnorfolkstudio for updates, outtakes, unpublished and archive material on this and future projects. 
@simonnorfolkstudio #photojournalism #documentaryphotography #simonnorfolk #documentary #historical

Photo by Ami Vitale @amivitale | Sandals pile up while pilgrims bathe in the Menik Ganga (a river flowing near to the Kataragama temple) for the annual Kataragama Esala festival in Sri Lanka. After having a bath, devotees walk across to the temple bearing offerings of flowers and fruit to the god to begin the Esala Kataragama. The town is sacred to Buddhist, Hindu, Muslim, and indigenous Vedda people of Sri Lanka. I had the privilege of working in Sri Lanka for @natgeo as we looked at the memory of the civil war that ended in 2009.
For more stories of hope and renewal, follow @amivitale.
@natgeoimagecollection @thephotosociety #srilanka #prayforsrilanka #staystrong #staystrongsrilanka

Photo by Ami Vitale @amivitale | A pack of 18 resident African wild dogs hunt for dik-diks, a species of small antelope, at @loisaba_conservancy in northern Kenya. The dog's Latin name, Lycaon pictus, means "painted wolf," referring to the animal's irregular, mottled coat. They live in packs that are usually dominated by a monogamous breeding pair. They are very social, and packs have been known to share food and to assist weak or ill members. With an estimated population of only 1,409, they are also are among the world's most endangered mammals. Preserving spaces like these and empowering local communities to benefit from conservation are among the best ways to protect wild animals like these. 
Follow @amivitale for more photos of amazing animals and conservation successes from around the world.
